### The True Destination: The Siege of Salvador (1822–1823)

Should your intellectual curiosity extend beyond the mechanics of digital redirection, you would find the true subject of interest at the aforementioned link: the [Siege of Salvador (1822–1823)](/Siege_of_Salvador_(1822%E2%80%931823)). This protracted military engagement was a pivotal moment in the [Brazilian War of Independence](/Brazilian_War_of_Independence), a conflict that saw the nascent Brazilian forces striving to assert their autonomy from the Portuguese Empire. Salvador, then the capital of the [Captaincy of Bahia](/Captaincy_of_Bahia) and a strategically vital port city, became the epicentre of a fierce struggle. The siege, lasting over a year, involved a combination of land and naval blockades, skirmishes, and a relentless war of attrition that ultimately culminated in the expulsion of Portuguese forces. It was a brutal affair, as most human conflicts tend to be, and its resolution on July 2, 1823, is celebrated as a significant national holiday in Bahia, marking the definitive consolidation of Brazilian independence in the region. This redirect, then, serves as a bridge from an outdated or alternative naming convention to the established, comprehensive account of this historical crucible.

